3 Image processing

3.1 Cilia Tracking

Cilia posses different properties that might be of interest in my study. What I want to know is how many cilia are there per Primordium and genotype and then maybe also where they are and how long they are. Quantification therefore has to take place in 3D. To quantify this I can think of two options, namely 3D object segmentation and tracking. Tracking might be a little contra intuitive since its mostly associated with tracking objects through time, but it can also be used to track objects through Z, if T and Z in the image properties are swapped. Since 3D object segmentation is quite time consuming I went for the tracking alternative, which is more straight forward. (Alternatively a neural network could be trained)

A short macro was written to prepare the data for analysis, it contains

  • cropping in X, Y and Z
  • clearing of signal outside the pLLP
  • swapping of T and Z

5 Data Processing

Data import

setwd("D:/David/170105_SN120_shr3+Arl13b_fixed/Tracking/Tables")
filelist <- list.files(".", pattern="*wt", full.names=FALSE)

The import function was altered to count the Track_IDs per emrbyo

library(plyr)
library(dplyr)
GT <- "++"
  read.data.all.count <- function(file){
    dat <- read.table(file, sep="\t", header=TRUE)
    dat$ID <- NULL
    dat$POSITION_Z <- NULL
    dat$RADIUS <- NULL
    dat$VISIBILITY <- NULL
    dat$MANUAL_COLOR <- NULL
    dat$Embryo <- file # add Emrbyo ID
    count <- ddply (.data=dat ,.variable=.(TRACK_ID),.fun=count)
    names(count)[2] <- "count"
    count$Embryo <- file # add Emrbyo ID
    count$GT <- GT # add Genotype
    return(count)
  }
SN120_Tracks_TRACKID_wt <- ldply(filelist, read.data.all.count)

Then the number (count) of the individual Embryos was deduced (equal to number of Tracks)

SN120_Tracks_count_wt <- ddply (.data=SN120_Tracks_TRACKID_wt ,.variable=.(Embryo, GT),.fun=count)
SN120_Tracks_stats_wt <- ddply(SN120_Tracks_TRACKID_wt, .(Embryo), summarize, mean=mean(count, na.rm=TRUE), sd=sd(count, na.rm=TRUE), GT="++")
